{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_Vgl9yerQyCFELKkPDwmJEdN6","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tPurpose & context\n2\tVasilis is planning a fully booked international trip in August 2026, traveling with a companion named Athina Mari. The trip spans Cairo (Egypt), Arusha and the northern Tanzania safari circuit, Zanzibar, and Dar es Salaam, running August 3–20. The trip combines cultural sightseeing in Cairo, a group camping safari through Tarangire, Lake Manyara, and Ngorongoro Crater, beach time in Zanzibar, and city exploration in Dar es Salaam. All flights, accommodations, the safari, and key dining are confirmed and fully organized.\n3\tVasilis communicates with Claude in both Greek and English interchangeably; Claude should respond in whichever language Vasilis uses.\n4\t\n5\tCurrent state\n6\tAll trip logistics are confirmed. No unbooked gaps remain.\n7\tFull flight itinerary (Vasileios Kefallinos + Athina Mari):\n8\t\n9\tAug 3: ATH→CAI, Aegean A3932, 06:55–08:50, ref ZZJQUU\n10\tAug 4: CAI→DAR, EgyptAir, 22:40–04:20+1\n11\tAug 5: DAR→ARK, Precision Air TC144, 10:50–12:00\n12\tAug 11: ARK→ZNZ, Precision Air TC145, 12:40–13:40\n13\tAug 19: DAR→CAI, EgyptAir, 05:20–11:05\n14\tAug 20: CAI→ATH, Aegean A3935, 19:55–22:00, ref ZZL22S\n15\tTotal flights: ~€2,707\n16\t\n17\tAll accommodations confirmed:\n18\t\n19\tEileen Hotel, Cairo — Aug 3–5 (fly out Aug 4 at 22:40; late checkout Aug 5 not used for sleep)\n20\tSerengeti Villa, Arusha — Aug 5–7 | Ph: +255 757 757 928\n21\tSafari (Aug 7–9): Suricata Safaris Ltd — Tarangire (Twiga Camp Site, FB) → Lake Manyara (Twiga Camp Site, FB) → Ngorongoro Crater (Jevas Hotel, HB)\n22\tKutoka Lodge, Arusha — Aug 9–11\n23\tTreasures of Zanzibar House — Aug 11–13\n24\tAyla Beach House, Zanzibar — Aug 13–17\n25\tSunny Shore B&B, Dar es Salaam — Aug 17–19\n26\tRamses Hilton, Cairo — Aug 19–20 (1 night)\n27\t\n28\tSafari: Suricata Safaris Ltd, 3-day group camping safari, Aug 7–9. Contact: Richard, +255 763 222 293, info@suricatasafaris.com. Cost: $1,200 total; $240 deposit paid (20%); $960 balance due on arrival in cash (USD, post-2009 notes) or online via Pesapal (+5% surcharge): payments.pesapal.com/suricatasafaris.\n29\tDining reservation: The Rock Restaurant, Zanzibar — Aug 15, 18:00–20:00 sitting, 2 adults, 2x Tropical Passion Fruit Cheesecake included. Fully paid ($46). Outdoor seating requested for sunset/star views. Contact: +255 776 591 360 / +255 763 070 658, booking@therockrestaurantzanzibar.com.\n30\tDriving in Zanzibar: Vasilis holds an International Driving Permit (IDP). A local Zanzibar Driving Permit is also required (~$15, valid up to 3 months). Most rental companies arrange this with a license photo provided 24+ hours before arrival. Police checkpoints are frequent; carry both IDP and local permit (screenshot acceptable).\n31\t\n32\tOn the horizon\n33\t\n34\tSafari balance ($960 USD, post-2009 notes) to be paid on arrival — cash preferred; Pesapal online adds 5%.\n35\tCairo Stopover 1 sightseeing plan: Grand Egyptian Museum and Pyramids of Giza (Aug 3–4). Eileen Hotel is near Tahrir Square/Nile Corniche.\n36\tCairo Stopover 2 sightseeing plan: Islamic Cairo, the Citadel, Khan el-Khalili bazaar, Coptic Cairo (Aug 19–20). Ramses Hilton is the base; taxi needed between Citadel and Coptic Cairo.\n37\tZanzibar activities and local exploration, including The Rock Restaurant dinner on Aug 15.\n38\tDar es Salaam: arriving by ferry from Zanzibar; interest in city exploration (Kivukoni Fish Market, Kariakoo Market, National Museum, Coco Beach, Bongoyo Island).\n39\t\n40\t\n41\tKey learnings & principles\n42\t\n43\tEgyptAir operates the Cairo↔Dar es Salaam legs — confirmed by Vasilis; do not second-guess this.\n44\tTanzania e-visa is mandatory online ($50/person) at visa.immigration.go.tz; visa-on-arrival no longer available as of January 2025. Zanzibar also requires separate mandatory travel insurance from the Zanzibar Insurance Corporation.\n45\tEgypt e-visa is multiple-entry ($65); both travelers apply separately. Egyptian e-visa requires a mandatory printed copy.\n46\tNgorongoro nights are cold — warm layers needed.\n47\tFor Zanzibar swimming: north coast (Nungwi area) offers more consistent conditions vs. east/south coasts where low tide limits access.\n48\tPrecision Air flights (TC144/TC145) have luggage restrictions favoring soft bags.\n49\tAugust is peak safari season — ideal for wildlife, including the Great Wildebeest Migration corridor.\n50\tVasilis prefers simple, concise output formats (bullet lists over tables) unless a table is specifically requested.\n51\t\n52\t\n53\tTools & resources\n54\t\n55\tSafari operator: Suricata Safaris Ltd — Richard (+255 763 222 293, info@suricatasafaris.com)\n56\tSafari payment: Pesapal (payments.pesapal.com/suricatasafaris) — 5% surcharge applies\n57\tEileen Hotel Cairo: +20 15 56434043, info@eileenhotel.com — 21 Youssef El-Gendy St, Abdeen, Downtown Cairo (near Tahrir Square)\n58\tSerengeti Villa Arusha: +255 757 757 928\n59\tThe Rock Restaurant Zanzibar: +255 776 591 360 / +255 763 070 658, booking@therockrestaurantzanzibar.com\n60\tZanzibar Insurance Corporation: for mandatory Zanzibar travel insurance\n61\tTanzania e-visa portal: visa.immigration.go.tz\n62\tEgypt e-visa portal: previously used for application\n63\tSafari clothing: Decathlon (Forclaz trekking line) recommended as primary source in Greece; DEET-based insect repellent essential"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4bfa69d9-de98-4976-b4ad-12c5314f8543","uuid":"05620ea6-9e10-43a7-a332-bc907c57e17f","timestamp":"2026-07-14T16:48:44.742Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/06-tanzania/fixtures/tanzaniamemories.md","content":"Purpose & context\nVasilis is planning a fully booked international trip in August 2026, traveling with a companion named Athina Mari. The trip spans Cairo (Egypt), Arusha and the northern Tanzania safari circuit, Zanzibar, and Dar es Salaam, running August 3–20. The trip combines cultural sightseeing in Cairo, a group camping safari through Tarangire, Lake Manyara, and Ngorongoro Crater, beach time in Zanzibar, and city exploration in Dar es Salaam. All flights, accommodations, the safari, and key dining are confirmed and fully organized.\nVasilis communicates with Claude in both Greek and English interchangeably; Claude should respond in whichever language Vasilis uses.\n\nCurrent state\nAll trip logistics are confirmed. No unbooked gaps remain.\nFull flight itinerary (Vasileios Kefallinos + Athina Mari):\n\nAug 3: ATH→CAI, Aegean A3932, 06:55–08:50, ref ZZJQUU\nAug 4: CAI→DAR, EgyptAir, 22:40–04:20+1\nAug 5: DAR→ARK, Precision Air TC144, 10:50–12:00\nAug 11: ARK→ZNZ, Precision Air TC145, 12:40–13:40\nAug 19: DAR→CAI, EgyptAir, 05:20–11:05\nAug 20: CAI→ATH, Aegean A3935, 19:55–22:00, ref ZZL22S\nTotal flights: ~€2,707\n\nAll accommodations confirmed:\n\nEileen Hotel, Cairo — Aug 3–5 (fly out Aug 4 at 22:40; late checkout Aug 5 not used for sleep)\nSerengeti Villa, Arusha — Aug 5–7 | Ph: +255 757 757 928\nSafari (Aug 7–9): Suricata Safaris Ltd — Tarangire (Twiga Camp Site, FB) → Lake Manyara (Twiga Camp Site, FB) → Ngorongoro Crater (Jevas Hotel, HB)\nKutoka Lodge, Arusha — Aug 9–11\nTreasures of Zanzibar House — Aug 11–13\nAyla Beach House, Zanzibar — Aug 13–17\nSunny Shore B&B, Dar es Salaam — Aug 17–19\nRamses Hilton, Cairo — Aug 19–20 (1 night)\n\nSafari: Suricata Safaris Ltd, 3-day group camping safari, Aug 7–9. Contact: Richard, +255 763 222 293, info@suricatasafaris.com. Cost: $1,200 total; $240 deposit paid (20%); $960 balance due on arrival in cash (USD, post-2009 notes) or online via Pesapal (+5% surcharge): payments.pesapal.com/suricatasafaris.\nDining reservation: The Rock Restaurant, Zanzibar — Aug 15, 18:00–20:00 sitting, 2 adults, 2x Tropical Passion Fruit Cheesecake included. Fully paid ($46). Outdoor seating requested for sunset/star views. Contact: +255 776 591 360 / +255 763 070 658, booking@therockrestaurantzanzibar.com.\nDriving in Zanzibar: Vasilis holds an International Driving Permit (IDP). A local Zanzibar Driving Permit is also required (~$15, valid up to 3 months). Most rental companies arrange this with a license photo provided 24+ hours before arrival. Police checkpoints are frequent; carry both IDP and local permit (screenshot acceptable).\n\nOn the horizon\n\nSafari balance ($960 USD, post-2009 notes) to be paid on arrival — cash preferred; Pesapal online adds 5%.\nCairo Stopover 1 sightseeing plan: Grand Egyptian Museum and Pyramids of Giza (Aug 3–4). Eileen Hotel is near Tahrir Square/Nile Corniche.\nCairo Stopover 2 sightseeing plan: Islamic Cairo, the Citadel, Khan el-Khalili bazaar, Coptic Cairo (Aug 19–20). Ramses Hilton is the base; taxi needed between Citadel and Coptic Cairo.\nZanzibar activities and local exploration, including The Rock Restaurant dinner on Aug 15.\nDar es Salaam: arriving by ferry from Zanzibar; interest in city exploration (Kivukoni Fish Market, Kariakoo Market, National Museum, Coco Beach, Bongoyo Island).\n\n\nKey learnings & principles\n\nEgyptAir operates the Cairo↔Dar es Salaam legs — confirmed by Vasilis; do not second-guess this.\nTanzania e-visa is mandatory online ($50/person) at visa.immigration.go.tz; visa-on-arrival no longer available as of January 2025. Zanzibar also requires separate mandatory travel insurance from the Zanzibar Insurance Corporation.\nEgypt e-visa is multiple-entry ($65); both travelers apply separately. Egyptian e-visa requires a mandatory printed copy.\nNgorongoro nights are cold — warm layers needed.\nFor Zanzibar swimming: north coast (Nungwi area) offers more consistent conditions vs. east/south coasts where low tide limits access.\nPrecision Air flights (TC144/TC145) have luggage restrictions favoring soft bags.\nAugust is peak safari season — ideal for wildlife, including the Great Wildebeest Migration corridor.\nVasilis prefers simple, concise output formats (bullet lists over tables) unless a table is specifically requested.\n\n\nTools & resources\n\nSafari operator: Suricata Safaris Ltd — Richard (+255 763 222 293, info@suricatasafaris.com)\nSafari payment: Pesapal (payments.pesapal.com/suricatasafaris) — 5% surcharge applies\nEileen Hotel Cairo: +20 15 56434043, info@eileenhotel.com — 21 Youssef El-Gendy St, Abdeen, Downtown Cairo (near Tahrir Square)\nSerengeti Villa Arusha: +255 757 757 928\nThe Rock Restaurant Zanzibar: +255 776 591 360 / +255 763 070 658, booking@therockrestaurantzanzibar.com\nZanzibar Insurance Corporation: for mandatory Zanzibar travel insurance\nTanzania e-visa portal: visa.immigration.go.tz\nEgypt e-visa portal: previously used for application\nSafari clothing: Decathlon (Forclaz trekking line) recommended as primary source in Greece; DEET-based insect repellent essential","numLines":63,"startLine":1,"totalLines":63}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_0G8pQHjFUyozuPAIz0Ai2xd4","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t/**\n2\t * lmthing.cloud gateway client — everything a scenario needs to stand up a disposable prod\n3\t * test user: register, provision the compute pod, load API keys into pod env, wake it.\n4\t *\n5\t * Budget note: scenarios burn real tokens. We deliberately load the **direct Azure** keys from\n6\t * `sdk/org/.env` into the pod env (AZURE_API_KEY + AZURE_RESOURCE_NAME + the LM_MODEL_* aliases),\n7\t * so agent traffic goes straight to Azure AI Foundry and never touches the per-user LiteLLM key\n8\t * that carries the tier budget. A user therefore does not \"run out\" mid-scenario. `budget()` is\n9\t * still exposed so a scenario can assert on spend, and `provisionUser()` is cheap enough to call\n10\t * again if a pod ever does get budget-capped.\n11\t */\n12\timport { readFileSync } from 'node:fs';\n13\timport { SDK_ORG } from './paths.mjs';\n14\timport { mintSession } from './jwt.mjs';\n15\timport { fetchResilient } from './pod.mjs';\n16\timport { LOCAL, LOCAL_BASE, ensureLocalServer } from './local.mjs';\n17\t\n18\texport const GATEWAY = process.env.LM_GATEWAY ?? 'https://lmthing.cloud';\n19\t\n20\tclass HttpError extends Error {\n21\t  constructor(method, url, status, body) {\n22\t    super(`${method} ${url} → ${status}: ${typeof body === 'string' ? body : JSON.stringify(body)}`);\n23\t    this.status = status;\n24\t    this.body = body;\n25\t  }\n26\t}\n27\t\n28\tasync function req(method, path, { token, body, base = GATEWAY } = {}) {\n29\t  const res = await fetchResilient(`${base}${path}`, {\n30\t    method,\n31\t    headers: {\n32\t      ...(body ? { 'content-type': 'application/json' } : {}),\n33\t      ...(token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${token}` } : {}),\n34\t    },\n35\t    ...(body ? { body: JSON.stringify(body) } : {}),\n36\t  });\n37\t  const text = await res.text();\n38\t  let parsed = text;\n39\t  try {\n40\t    parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n41\t  } catch {\n42\t    /* keep raw text */\n43\t  }\n44\t  if (!res.ok) throw new HttpError(method, path, res.status, parsed);\n45\t  return parsed;\n46\t}\n47\t\n48\t/** Parse `sdk/org/.env` into a plain object (no dotenv dep; ignores comments + blanks). */\n49\texport function readSdkEnv() {\n50\t  const raw = readFileSync(`${SDK_ORG}/.env`, 'utf8');\n51\t  const out = {};\n52\t  for (const line of raw.split('\\n')) {\n53\t    const m = /^\\s*([A-Z0-9_]+)\\s*=\\s*(.*)\\s*$/.exec(line);\n54\t    if (!m) continue; // comment or blank\n55\t    out[m[1]] = m[2].replace(/^[\"']|[\"']$/g, '');\n56\t  }\n57\t  return out;\n58\t}\n59\t\n60\t/**\n61\t * The env vars a pod needs to run agents against Azure directly (budget-free), plus web search.\n62\t * Anything absent from sdk/org/.env is simply omitted.\n63\t */\n64\texport function agentEnvFromSdk() {\n65\t  const env = readSdkEnv();\n66\t  const keys = [\n67\t    'AZURE_API_KEY',\n68\t    'AZURE_RESOURCE_NAME',\n69\t    'TAVILY_API_KEY',\n70\t    'LM_MODEL_XS',\n71\t    'LM_MODEL_S',\n72\t    'LM_MODEL_M',\n73\t    'LM_MODEL_L',\n74\t    'LM_MODEL_M_R',\n75\t    'LM_MODEL_L_R',\n76\t    'LM_MODEL_VISION',\n77\t    'LM_TRANSCRIBE_MODEL',\n78\t  ];\n79\t  const out = {};\n80\t  for (const k of keys) if (env[k]) out[k] = env[k];\n81\t  return out;\n82\t}\n83\t\n84\t/** `POST /api/auth/register` → { user_id, api_key }. Login is broken in prod; we mint instead. */\n85\texport async function register(email, password) {\n86\t  return req('POST', '/api/auth/register', { body: { email, password } });\n87\t}\n88\t\n89\texport const ensurePod = (token) => req('POST', '/api/compute/ensure', { token });\n90\texport const podStatus = (token) => req('GET', '/api/compute/status', { token });\n91\texport const wakePod = (token) => req('POST', '/api/compute/wake', { token });\n92\t\n93\t/**\n94\t * Remaining LiteLLM budget. NOTE this lives on the POD (`routes/budget.ts` relays the caller's\n95\t * Authorization to the gateway and computes the line with the master key) — there is no\n96\t * `/api/budget` on the gateway itself. Scenarios run on direct Azure keys, so this is\n97\t * informational: it tells you whether the tier key is exhausted, not whether the run can proceed.\n98\t */\n99\texport const budget = (token) => req('GET', '/api/budget', { token, base: podBase() });\n100\t\n101\t/**\n102\t * `PUT /api/compute/env` REPLACES the whole var set, so always GET-merge-PUT — clobbering the\n103\t * gateway-injected lmthingcloud creds would break the pod.\n104\t *\n105\t * A PUT rolls the deployment, and pod sessions are IN-MEMORY: any session created against the\n106\t * old pod dies with it (`GET /api/sessions/:id/events` → 404 unknown session). So we skip the\n107\t * write entirely when nothing would change — which is the common case on a reused test user.\n108\t *\n109\t * @returns {{merged: object, changed: boolean}}\n110\t */\n111\texport async function mergePodEnv(token, vars) {\n112\t  const current = await req('GET', '/api/compute/env', { token }).catch(() => ({ vars: {} }));\n113\t  const existing = current.vars ?? {};\n114\t  const merged = { ...existing, ...vars };\n115\t  const changed = Object.entries(merged).some(([k, v]) => existing[k] !== v);\n116\t  if (!changed) return { merged, changed: false };\n117\t  await req('PUT', '/api/compute/env', { token, body: { vars: merged } });\n118\t  return { merged, changed: true };\n119\t}\n120\t\n121\t/**\n122\t * Wait until a session created NOW would survive — i.e. the env-triggered rollout is finished.\n123\t *\n124\t * There is no reliable \"which pod process am I talking to\" signal from outside, and the gateway's\n125\t * `pod.ready` (readyReplicas > 0) stays true across a rolling update because the OLD replica is\n126\t * still ready. So we test the property we actually need, directly: create a probe session, wait,\n127\t * and confirm it still exists. If the pod rolled under us, the probe vanishes and we retry.\n128\t */\n129\texport async function waitPodSettled(token, base = podBase(), { attempts = 6, settleMs = 9_000 } = {}) {\n130\t  const headers = { authorization: `Bearer ${token}`, 'content-type': 'application/json' };\n131\t  for (let i = 0; i < attempts; i++) {\n132\t    try {\n133\t      const res = await fetch(`${base}/api/sessions`, {\n134\t        method: 'POST',\n135\t        headers,\n136\t        body: JSON.stringify({ projectId: 'user' }),\n137\t      });\n138\t      if (res.ok) {\n139\t        const { sessionId } = await res.json();\n140\t        await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, settleMs));\n141\t        const list = await fetch(`${base}/api/sessions`, { headers }).then((r) => r.json());\n142\t        const alive = (list.sessions ?? []).some((s) => s.sessionId === sessionId);\n143\t        if (alive) {\n144\t          // Clean up the probe so it doesn't pollute the scenario's session list.\n145\t          await fetch(`${base}/api/sessions/${sessionId}`, { method: 'DELETE', headers }).catch(() => {});\n146\t          return true;\n147\t        }\n148\t      }\n149\t    } catch {\n150\t      /* pod mid-roll — retry */\n151\t    }\n152\t    await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 5_000));\n153\t  }\n154\t  throw new Error('pod never settled: a freshly created session keeps disappearing');\n155\t}\n156\t\n157\t/**\n158\t * Poll until the gateway reports the pod ready (or throw).\n159\t *\n160\t * Readiness lives at `status.pod.ready` / `status.pod.stage === 'ready'` — NOT at the top level.\n161\t * Note \"ready\" here means readyReplicas>0, which precedes Envoy actually wiring the woken\n162\t * endpoint (see the pod-readiness-edge race); callers that immediately hit the pod should\n163\t * tolerate one early 503, which `Pod.req` surfaces as a normal HttpError.\n164\t */\n165\texport async function waitPodReady(token, { timeoutMs = 180_000, intervalMs = 3_000 } = {}) {\n166\t  const deadline = Date.now() + timeoutMs;\n167\t  let last;\n168\t  while (Date.now() < deadline) {\n169\t    try {\n170\t      last = await podStatus(token);\n171\t      if (last?.pod?.ready || last?.pod?.stage === 'ready') return last;\n172\t    } catch (err) {\n173\t      last = { error: String(err) };\n174\t    }\n175\t    await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, intervalMs));\n176\t  }\n177\t  throw new Error(`pod not ready after ${timeoutMs}ms: ${JSON.stringify(last)}`);\n178\t}\n179\t\n180\t/**\n181\t * Full disposable-test-user provision: register → mint session → ensure pod → load agent keys →\n182\t * wait ready. Returns everything a scenario needs, including a `pod` base URL.\n183\t *\n184\t * Pods are reached through the chat origin: Envoy validates the JWT and routes on the `sub` claim\n185\t * to `lmthing.user-<id>.svc`, waking a scaled-to-zero pod on the way.\n186\t */\n187\texport async function provisionUser({ label = 'scn', password = 'Test-Passw0rd!' } = {}) {\n188\t  // Local target: no register, no JWT, no pod env PUT. Bring up (or attach to) the one shared\n189\t  // `lmthing serve`, which reads sdk/org/.env for the Azure keys itself. The pod does no auth, so\n190\t  // token is null; lanes are isolated by projectId, not by user, on this single server.\n191\t  if (LOCAL) {\n192\t    await ensureLocalServer();\n193\t    return { email: `${label}@local`, password, userId: `local-${label}`, session: null, token: null, pod: LOCAL_BASE };\n194\t  }\n195\t  const email = `${label}-${Date.now().toString(36)}@lmthing.test`;\n196\t  const { user_id: userId } = await register(email, password);\n197\t  const session = mintSession(userId, email);\n198\t  await ensurePod(session.accessToken);\n199\t  // Pod env must be loaded BEFORE the first agent turn: the PUT rolls the pod, and a restart\n200\t  // mid-scenario destroys in-memory sessions (it would look like a spurious failure).\n201\t  const { changed } = await mergePodEnv(session.accessToken, agentEnvFromSdk());\n202\t  await waitPodReady(session.accessToken);\n203\t  if (changed) await waitPodSettled(session.accessToken);\n204\t  return { email, password, userId, session, token: session.accessToken, pod: podBase() };\n205\t}\n206\t\n207\t/** The origin that fronts a user's pod (Envoy routes by JWT `sub`; local → the shared serve). */\n208\texport const podBase = () => process.env.LM_POD_BASE ?? (LOCAL ? LOCAL_BASE : 'https://lmthing.chat');\n209\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4bfa69d9-de98-4976-b4ad-12c5314f8543","uuid":"07cbd19f-4513-470a-85d6-209cda8fd68d","timestamp":"2026-07-14T16:48:44.745Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/lib/gateway.mjs","content":"/**\n * lmthing.cloud gateway client — everything a scenario needs to stand up a disposable prod\n * test user: register, provision the compute pod, load API keys into pod env, wake it.\n *\n * Budget note: scenarios burn real tokens. We deliberately load the **direct Azure** keys from\n * `sdk/org/.env` into the pod env (AZURE_API_KEY + AZURE_RESOURCE_NAME + the LM_MODEL_* aliases),\n * so agent traffic goes straight to Azure AI Foundry and never touches the per-user LiteLLM key\n * that carries the tier budget. A user therefore does not \"run out\" mid-scenario. `budget()` is\n * still exposed so a scenario can assert on spend, and `provisionUser()` is cheap enough to call\n * again if a pod ever does get budget-capped.\n */\nimport { readFileSync } from 'node:fs';\nimport { SDK_ORG } from './paths.mjs';\nimport { mintSession } from './jwt.mjs';\nimport { fetchResilient } from './pod.mjs';\nimport { LOCAL, LOCAL_BASE, ensureLocalServer } from './local.mjs';\n\nexport const GATEWAY = process.env.LM_GATEWAY ?? 'https://lmthing.cloud';\n\nclass HttpError extends Error {\n  constructor(method, url, status, body) {\n    super(`${method} ${url} → ${status}: ${typeof body === 'string' ? body : JSON.stringify(body)}`);\n    this.status = status;\n    this.body = body;\n  }\n}\n\nasync function req(method, path, { token, body, base = GATEWAY } = {}) {\n  const res = await fetchResilient(`${base}${path}`, {\n    method,\n    headers: {\n      ...(body ? { 'content-type': 'application/json' } : {}),\n      ...(token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${token}` } : {}),\n    },\n    ...(body ? { body: JSON.stringify(body) } : {}),\n  });\n  const text = await res.text();\n  let parsed = text;\n  try {\n    parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n  } catch {\n    /* keep raw text */\n  }\n  if (!res.ok) throw new HttpError(method, path, res.status, parsed);\n  return parsed;\n}\n\n/** Parse `sdk/org/.env` into a plain object (no dotenv dep; ignores comments + blanks). */\nexport function readSdkEnv() {\n  const raw = readFileSync(`${SDK_ORG}/.env`, 'utf8');\n  const out = {};\n  for (const line of raw.split('\\n')) {\n    const m = /^\\s*([A-Z0-9_]+)\\s*=\\s*(.*)\\s*$/.exec(line);\n    if (!m) continue; // comment or blank\n    out[m[1]] = m[2].replace(/^[\"']|[\"']$/g, '');\n  }\n  return out;\n}\n\n/**\n * The env vars a pod needs to run agents against Azure directly (budget-free), plus web search.\n * Anything absent from sdk/org/.env is simply omitted.\n */\nexport function agentEnvFromSdk() {\n  const env = readSdkEnv();\n  const keys = [\n    'AZURE_API_KEY',\n    'AZURE_RESOURCE_NAME',\n    'TAVILY_API_KEY',\n    'LM_MODEL_XS',\n    'LM_MODEL_S',\n    'LM_MODEL_M',\n    'LM_MODEL_L',\n    'LM_MODEL_M_R',\n    'LM_MODEL_L_R',\n    'LM_MODEL_VISION',\n    'LM_TRANSCRIBE_MODEL',\n  ];\n  const out = {};\n  for (const k of keys) if (env[k]) out[k] = env[k];\n  return out;\n}\n\n/** `POST /api/auth/register` → { user_id, api_key }. Login is broken in prod; we mint instead. */\nexport async function register(email, password) {\n  return req('POST', '/api/auth/register', { body: { email, password } });\n}\n\nexport const ensurePod = (token) => req('POST', '/api/compute/ensure', { token });\nexport const podStatus = (token) => req('GET', '/api/compute/status', { token });\nexport const wakePod = (token) => req('POST', '/api/compute/wake', { token });\n\n/**\n * Remaining LiteLLM budget. NOTE this lives on the POD (`routes/budget.ts` relays the caller's\n * Authorization to the gateway and computes the line with the master key) — there is no\n * `/api/budget` on the gateway itself. Scenarios run on direct Azure keys, so this is\n * informational: it tells you whether the tier key is exhausted, not whether the run can proceed.\n */\nexport const budget = (token) => req('GET', '/api/budget', { token, base: podBase() });\n\n/**\n * `PUT /api/compute/env` REPLACES the whole var set, so always GET-merge-PUT — clobbering the\n * gateway-injected lmthingcloud creds would break the pod.\n *\n * A PUT rolls the deployment, and pod sessions are IN-MEMORY: any session created against the\n * old pod dies with it (`GET /api/sessions/:id/events` → 404 unknown session). So we skip the\n * write entirely when nothing would change — which is the common case on a reused test user.\n *\n * @returns {{merged: object, changed: boolean}}\n */\nexport async function mergePodEnv(token, vars) {\n  const current = await req('GET', '/api/compute/env', { token }).catch(() => ({ vars: {} }));\n  const existing = current.vars ?? {};\n  const merged = { ...existing, ...vars };\n  const changed = Object.entries(merged).some(([k, v]) => existing[k] !== v);\n  if (!changed) return { merged, changed: false };\n  await req('PUT', '/api/compute/env', { token, body: { vars: merged } });\n  return { merged, changed: true };\n}\n\n/**\n * Wait until a session created NOW would survive — i.e. the env-triggered rollout is finished.\n *\n * There is no reliable \"which pod process am I talking to\" signal from outside, and the gateway's\n * `pod.ready` (readyReplicas > 0) stays true across a rolling update because the OLD replica is\n * still ready. So we test the property we actually need, directly: create a probe session, wait,\n * and confirm it still exists. If the pod rolled under us, the probe vanishes and we retry.\n */\nexport async function waitPodSettled(token, base = podBase(), { attempts = 6, settleMs = 9_000 } = {}) {\n  const headers = { authorization: `Bearer ${token}`, 'content-type': 'application/json' };\n  for (let i = 0; i < attempts; i++) {\n    try {\n      const res = await fetch(`${base}/api/sessions`, {\n        method: 'POST',\n        headers,\n        body: JSON.stringify({ projectId: 'user' }),\n      });\n      if (res.ok) {\n        const { sessionId } = await res.json();\n        await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, settleMs));\n        const list = await fetch(`${base}/api/sessions`, { headers }).then((r) => r.json());\n        const alive = (list.sessions ?? []).some((s) => s.sessionId === sessionId);\n        if (alive) {\n          // Clean up the probe so it doesn't pollute the scenario's session list.\n          await fetch(`${base}/api/sessions/${sessionId}`, { method: 'DELETE', headers }).catch(() => {});\n          return true;\n        }\n      }\n    } catch {\n      /* pod mid-roll — retry */\n    }\n    await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 5_000));\n  }\n  throw new Error('pod never settled: a freshly created session keeps disappearing');\n}\n\n/**\n * Poll until the gateway reports the pod ready (or throw).\n *\n * Readiness lives at `status.pod.ready` / `status.pod.stage === 'ready'` — NOT at the top level.\n * Note \"ready\" here means readyReplicas>0, which precedes Envoy actually wiring the woken\n * endpoint (see the pod-readiness-edge race); callers that immediately hit the pod should\n * tolerate one early 503, which `Pod.req` surfaces as a normal HttpError.\n */\nexport async function waitPodReady(token, { timeoutMs = 180_000, intervalMs = 3_000 } = {}) {\n  const deadline = Date.now() + timeoutMs;\n  let last;\n  while (Date.now() < deadline) {\n    try {\n      last = await podStatus(token);\n      if (last?.pod?.ready || last?.pod?.stage === 'ready') return last;\n    } catch (err) {\n      last = { error: String(err) };\n    }\n    await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, intervalMs));\n  }\n  throw new Error(`pod not ready after ${timeoutMs}ms: ${JSON.stringify(last)}`);\n}\n\n/**\n * Full disposable-test-user provision: register → mint session → ensure pod → load agent keys →\n * wait ready. Returns everything a scenario needs, including a `pod` base URL.\n *\n * Pods are reached through the chat origin: Envoy validates the JWT and routes on the `sub` claim\n * to `lmthing.user-<id>.svc`, waking a scaled-to-zero pod on the way.\n */\nexport async function provisionUser({ label = 'scn', password = 'Test-Passw0rd!' } = {}) {\n  // Local target: no register, no JWT, no pod env PUT. Bring up (or attach to) the one shared\n  // `lmthing serve`, which reads sdk/org/.env for the Azure keys itself. The pod does no auth, so\n  // token is null; lanes are isolated by projectId, not by user, on this single server.\n  if (LOCAL) {\n    await ensureLocalServer();\n    return { email: `${label}@local`, password, userId: `local-${label}`, session: null, token: null, pod: LOCAL_BASE };\n  }\n  const email = `${label}-${Date.now().toString(36)}@lmthing.test`;\n  const { user_id: userId } = await register(email, password);\n  const session = mintSession(userId, email);\n  await ensurePod(session.accessToken);\n  // Pod env must be loaded BEFORE the first agent turn: the PUT rolls the pod, and a restart\n  // mid-scenario destroys in-memory sessions (it would look like a spurious failure).\n  const { changed } = await mergePodEnv(session.accessToken, agentEnvFromSdk());\n  await waitPodReady(session.accessToken);\n  if (changed) await waitPodSettled(session.accessToken);\n  return { email, password, userId, session, token: session.accessToken, pod: podBase() };\n}\n\n/** The origin that fronts a user's pod (Envoy routes by JWT `sub`; local → the shared serve). */\nexport const podBase = () => process.env.LM_POD_BASE ?? (LOCAL ? LOCAL_BASE : 'https://lmthing.chat');\n","numLines":209,"startLine":1,"totalLines":209}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_0vKJymhQPLOI3qzqDReAbJ5i","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t#!/usr/bin/env node\n2\t/**\n3\t * Harness smoke test — proves the whole chain works before any scenario burns an hour on it:\n4\t * register → pod → env → THING session → a real LLM turn → trace assertions.\n5\t *\n6\t *   node smoke.mjs [label]\n7\t *\n8\t * If this fails, no scenario can pass; fix the harness first.\n9\t */\n10\timport { Pod } from './lib/pod.mjs';\n11\timport { ThingSession, approveAllConsent } from './lib/thing.mjs';\n12\timport { Report } from './lib/report.mjs';\n13\timport { getUser } from './provision.mjs';\n14\timport { budget } from './lib/gateway.mjs';\n15\t\n16\tconst label = process.argv[2] ?? 'smoke';\n17\tconst r = new Report('smoke', 'Harness smoke test');\n18\t\n19\tr.step('provision', 'a fresh prod user with a ready pod and Azure keys loaded');\n20\tconst user = await getUser(label);\n21\tr.check('user registered', !!user.userId, user.userId);\n22\tr.check('pod reachable', !!user.pod, user.pod);\n23\t\n24\tconst pod = new Pod({ base: user.pod, token: user.token });\n25\t\n26\tr.step('pod API', 'projects + store catalog answer over the Envoy-routed origin');\n27\tconst projects = await pod.listProjects();\n28\tr.check('GET /api/projects', Array.isArray(projects.projects ?? projects), JSON.stringify(projects).slice(0, 200));\n29\tconst store = await pod.storeSpaces();\n30\tconst spaces = store.spaces ?? [];\n31\tr.check('store catalog non-empty', spaces.length > 0, `${spaces.length} spaces`);\n32\tr.note(`catalog: ${spaces.map((s) => s.id).join(', ')}`);\n33\t\n34\tr.step('THING turn', 'a real LLM turn completes and the trace shows llm calls + a display');\n35\tconst thing = new ThingSession(pod, { verbose: true, onAsk: approveAllConsent });\n36\tawait thing.start();\n37\tconst turn = await thing.send('In one sentence: what can you help me build?', { timeoutMs: 240_000 });\n38\tr.check('turn completed', true, `${(turn.durationMs / 1000).toFixed(1)}s`);\n39\tr.check('LLM was called', turn.llmCalls > 0, `${turn.llmCalls} calls`);\n40\tr.check('THING replied', turn.text.length > 0, turn.text.slice(0, 200));\n41\tr.check('no eval errors', turn.errors.length === 0, JSON.stringify(turn.errors).slice(0, 300));\n42\tr.metric('first turn', (turn.durationMs / 1000).toFixed(1), 's');\n43\tr.metric('tokens', `${turn.tokens.in} in / ${turn.tokens.out} out`);\n44\t\n45\tconst b = await budget(user.token).catch((e) => ({ error: String(e) }));\n46\tr.note(`budget: ${JSON.stringify(b)}`);\n47\t\n48\tr.save(`${new URL('.', import.meta.url).pathname}.state/smoke-report.md`);\n49\tprocess.exit(r.passed ? 0 : 1);\n50\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4bfa69d9-de98-4976-b4ad-12c5314f8543","uuid":"8c0c0edb-3792-4aa5-8e49-4b0b8ce7b764","timestamp":"2026-07-14T16:48:44.746Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/smoke.mjs","content":"#!/usr/bin/env node\n/**\n * Harness smoke test — proves the whole chain works before any scenario burns an hour on it:\n * register → pod → env → THING session → a real LLM turn → trace assertions.\n *\n *   node smoke.mjs [label]\n *\n * If this fails, no scenario can pass; fix the harness first.\n */\nimport { Pod } from './lib/pod.mjs';\nimport { ThingSession, approveAllConsent } from './lib/thing.mjs';\nimport { Report } from './lib/report.mjs';\nimport { getUser } from './provision.mjs';\nimport { budget } from './lib/gateway.mjs';\n\nconst label = process.argv[2] ?? 'smoke';\nconst r = new Report('smoke', 'Harness smoke test');\n\nr.step('provision', 'a fresh prod user with a ready pod and Azure keys loaded');\nconst user = await getUser(label);\nr.check('user registered', !!user.userId, user.userId);\nr.check('pod reachable', !!user.pod, user.pod);\n\nconst pod = new Pod({ base: user.pod, token: user.token });\n\nr.step('pod API', 'projects + store catalog answer over the Envoy-routed origin');\nconst projects = await pod.listProjects();\nr.check('GET /api/projects', Array.isArray(projects.projects ?? projects), JSON.stringify(projects).slice(0, 200));\nconst store = await pod.storeSpaces();\nconst spaces = store.spaces ?? [];\nr.check('store catalog non-empty', spaces.length > 0, `${spaces.length} spaces`);\nr.note(`catalog: ${spaces.map((s) => s.id).join(', ')}`);\n\nr.step('THING turn', 'a real LLM turn completes and the trace shows llm calls + a display');\nconst thing = new ThingSession(pod, { verbose: true, onAsk: approveAllConsent });\nawait thing.start();\nconst turn = await thing.send('In one sentence: what can you help me build?', { timeoutMs: 240_000 });\nr.check('turn completed', true, `${(turn.durationMs / 1000).toFixed(1)}s`);\nr.check('LLM was called', turn.llmCalls > 0, `${turn.llmCalls} calls`);\nr.check('THING replied', turn.text.length > 0, turn.text.slice(0, 200));\nr.check('no eval errors', turn.errors.length === 0, JSON.stringify(turn.errors).slice(0, 300));\nr.metric('first turn', (turn.durationMs / 1000).toFixed(1), 's');\nr.metric('tokens', `${turn.tokens.in} in / ${turn.tokens.out} out`);\n\nconst b = await budget(user.token).catch((e) => ({ error: String(e) }));\nr.note(`budget: ${JSON.stringify(b)}`);\n\nr.save(`${new URL('.', import.meta.url).pathname}.state/smoke-report.md`);\nprocess.exit(r.passed ? 0 : 1);\n","numLines":50,"startLine":1,"totalLines":50}}}
