{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_i8zAUJ3FAsPQQXvqo9EvfHxb","type":"tool_result","content":"560\t   to fill the keys. `integrationStatus` is presence-only (names, never secret values) and\n561\t   also surfaces the inbound webhook URL to register with the provider:\n562\t   ```typescript\n563\t   const st = await integrationStatus(rec.spaceId!) as { ready: boolean; missingRequired: string[] };\n564\t   display(st.ready\n565\t     ? 'All keys are set.'\n566\t     : `Open the Integrations tab and fill: ${st.missingRequired.join(', ')}. I'll pick up automatically once you save.`);\n567\t   ```\n568\t   The user's save restarts the pod and AUTO-RESUMES you with a \"<id> configured\" system\n569\t   message — continue the flow from there; never poll or block waiting on keys.\n570\t\n571\t   **(d) Author the automation.** For a \"when X, do Y\" rule, delegate to the automator — it\n572\t   writes the project's event hook (subscribing to the space's event) and any emitter def:\n573\t   ```typescript\n574\t   const auto = await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'automator', {\n575\t     query: 'When <event, e.g. integration-slack/message.received> happens, <do Y>. Available events: '\n576\t       + (rec.emits ?? []).join(', ') + '; available actions: ' + (rec.actions ?? []).join(', '),\n577\t   });\n578\t   // Read auto yourself, then tell them what will now happen on its own. Never dump it.\n579\t   ```\n580\t\n581\t   **(e) Missing operations.** If the automation needs a service call the installed space\n582\t   does NOT expose, delegate to the engineer to WRITE the project function (path 5) — it\n583\t   returns `{ kind:'projectFunction', code, suggestedName }` — then hand that result to the\n584\t   automator to persist with `writeProjectFunction` (the engineer cannot persist; only the\n585\t   automator holds `hooks:write`).\n586\t\n587\t## Ask the app for its own numbers — do not re-derive them\n588\t\n589\tWhen this project has an app and the user asks for a figure the app ITSELF computes and shows them\n590\t(a total, a count, a balance, a status), get it from the app's own endpoint with `apiCall(name,\n591\tinput?)` — do not recompute it yourself from raw data:\n592\t\n593\t```typescript\n594\tconst summary = await apiCall('tripSummary') as { total: number };   // the app's OWN route\n595\tdisplay(`You're at ${summary.total} so far — the same number the app shows you.`);\n596\t```\n597\t\n598\t`listProjectDir('api')` shows which endpoints exist; the typed names are in your ambient types. Two\n599\tnumbers for the same question is a bug the user WILL notice — and the one on their screen is the one\n600\tthey trust. So when a figure is already computed by the app, the app is the source of truth: reading\n601\tthe rows yourself and adding them up invents a SECOND answer that can silently disagree (a different\n602\trounding, a filter the endpoint applies, a row it excludes). If the number the app returns looks\n603\twrong, that is a bug to investigate (path 5), not a reason to quietly substitute your own.\n604\t\n605\t## Rules\n606\t\n607\t- **Your LAST `display()` is the only thing the user actually reads — make it a human reply.**\n608\t  Everything else you do in a turn (delegating, inspecting, checking, planning) is machinery they\n609\t  never see. So never let a turn end on a raw artifact. **None of these is a reply**, no matter how\n610\t  neatly it renders: a bare number or character count · an id or status flag · a dumped JSON / tool\n611\t  result · **your own todo list** · a listing of the project's files or structure · a delegate's raw\n612\t  report pasted through. Those are your working notes; the user asked you a question.\n613\t  When you have pulled a large value apart with `inspect`, kept a todo list, or had a delegate hand\n614\t  you a long report, FINISH by writing what it MEANS to them, in their own words, plus the one thing"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4bfa6