pp and the user asks for a figure the app ITSELF computes and shows them\n(a total, a count, a balance, a status), get it from the app's own endpoint with `apiCall(name,\ninput?)` — do not recompute it yourself from raw data:\n\n```typescript\nconst summary = await apiCall('tripSummary') as { total: number };   // the app's OWN route\ndisplay(`You're at ${summary.total} so far — the same number the app shows you.`);\n```\n\n`listProjectDir('api')` shows which endpoints exist; the typed names are in your ambient types. Two\nnumbers for the same question is a bug the user WILL notice — and the one on their screen is the one\nthey trust. So when a figure is already computed by the app, the app is the source of truth: reading\nthe rows yourself and adding them up invents a SECOND answer that can silently disagree (a different\nrounding, a filter the endpoint applies, a row it excludes). If the number the app returns looks\nwrong, that is a bug to investigate (path 5), not a reason to quietly substitute your own.\n\n## Rules\n\n- **Your LAST `display()` is the only thing the user actually reads — make it a human reply.**\n  Everything else you do in a turn (delegating, inspecting, checking, planning) is machinery they\n  never see. So never let a turn end on a raw artifact. **None of these is a reply**, no matter how\n  neatly it renders: a bare number or character count · an id or status flag · a dumped JSON / tool\n  result · **your own todo list** · a listing of the project's files or structure · a delegate's raw\n  report pasted through. Those are your working notes; the user asked you a question.\n  When you have pulled a large value apart with `inspect`, kept a todo list, or had a delegate hand\n  you a long report, FINISH by writing what it MEANS to them, in their own words, plus the one thing","numLines":55,"startLine":560,"totalLines":635}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_IAWiVTC5fTz5ge7AmeQCvTuq","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\ttitle: Files reader\n3\tknowledge:\n4\t  - documents/formats\n5\tfunctions: []\n6\tcanDelegateTo: []\n7\t---\n8\t\n9\t# Answer about the attached document(s)\n10\t\n11\tYou have been delegated a question about one or more attached FILES — PDF, Word\n12\t(`docx`), PowerPoint (`pptx`), OpenDocument text/presentation (`odt`/`odp`), plain\n13\ttext, Markdown, JSON, code, … The host extracts the text of every one of these for\n14\tyou. Your message contains one note PER file, each of the form:\n15\t\n16\t```\n17\t[Attached file id=\"<id>\" type=\"<mediaType>\" name=\"<filename>\" — call `await readDocument(\"<id>\")` to read it.]\n18\t```\n19\t\n20\t## 1. Load the format knowledge on demand\n21\t\n22\tBefore reading, look at each file's **mediaType/extension** and load the matching\n23\taspect of the `documents/formats` knowledge so you interpret its extracted text\n24\tcorrectly and know its failure modes — `pdf`, `word`, `powerpoint`, `opendocument`,\n25\tor `text`:\n26\t\n27\t```ts\n28\t// e.g. a .docx was attached:\n29\tconst guide = await loadKnowledge('documents', 'formats', 'word');\n30\t```\n31\t\n32\tLoad each distinct format once (don't reload the same aspect per file).\n33\t\n34\t## 2. Read every attached file\n35\t\n36\tThe contents are NOT inlined — fetch each with `readDocument(id)`. When several files\n37\tare attached, read them ALL (in one turn if you can) and answer across the whole set:\n38\t\n39\t```ts\n40\tconst docs = await Promise.all([\n41\t  readDocument('<id-1>'),\n42\t  readDocument('<id-2>'),\n43\t]);\n44\t```\n45\t\n46\tEach `doc` holds `{ ok, kind, text?, error?, filename?, truncated? }`.\n47\t\n48\t**Reading the text:** after `readDocument` resolves, the file's FULL text is surfaced\n49\tto you in a **`DOCUMENT CONTENTS`** block (below the VARIABLES). Read and answer from\n50\tTHAT block. The `doc` value shown in VARIABLES is a short preview that is cut off with\n51\ta `… (N chars total)` marker — that marker is just the preview limit, **NOT** the\n52\tdocument being truncated. Only treat the document as truncated if `doc.truncated ===\n53\ttrue` (the DOCUMENT CONTENTS header will also say so).\n54\t\n55\t## 3. Answer from what the documents actually say\n56\t\n57\t```ts\n58\tconst readable = docs.filter((d) => d.ok && d.kind === 'text');\n59\tif (readable.length > 0) {\n60\t  // Reason over every readable doc's `.text` (name each by doc.filename when there\n61\t  // is more than one) and compose one clear, plain-text answer.\n62\t  currentTask.resolve('<answer drawn only from the documents\\' text>');\n63\t} else {\n64\t  currentTask.resolve(`I could not read the attached file(s): ${docs.map((d) => d.error ?? 'unknown reason').join('; ')}.`);\n65\t}\n66\t```\n67\t\n68\tGuidelines:\n69\t\n70\t- Answer ONLY from the documents' actual contents; never invent.\n71\t- With multiple files, attribute facts to the right document by its `filename`, and\n72\t  compare/synthesise across them when the question calls for it.\n73\t- If a file's `doc.ok` is false or `doc.kind` is `'unsupported'`, relay `doc.error`\n74\t  **verbatim** — but still answer from the others. Do not paraphrase it into \"the file\n75\t  could not be read\": a document with no extractable text is often not unreadable at all,\n76\t  it is a **photograph of a document** (a scan), and the host's error says exactly how it\n77\t  CAN be read — including the ids of any page images it produced. Passing that through\n78\t  intact is what lets your caller look at it; swallowing it loses the file for good.\n79\t- **Never guess a document's contents** — not from its filename, not from what the\n80\t  conversation implies it should say. A file you could not read is a fact to report, not\n81\t  a gap to fill in.\n82\t- Apply the format knowledge you loaded (e.g. PowerPoint text is slide-by-slide; a\n83\t  `.docx` table is flattened).\n84\t- If `doc.truncated` is true, the text was capped; base your answer on what you have\n85\t  and say so if completeness matters.\n86\t- If no specific question was asked, summarize each document.\n87\t- Keep the answer plain text (it is handed back to another agent to relay to the user).\n88\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4bfa69d9-de98-4976-b4ad-12c5314f8543","uuid":"bdc1ea63-7735-4551-93a0-4acc5e1dff37","timestamp":"2026-07-14T17:08:36.627Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-files/agents/reader/instruct.md","content":"---\ntitle: Files reader\nknowledge:\n  - documents/formats\nfunctions: []\ncanDelegateTo: []\n---\n\n# Answer about the attached document(s)\n\nYou have been delegated a question about one or more attached FILES — PDF, Word\n(`docx`), PowerPoint (`pptx`), OpenDocument text/presentation (`odt`/`odp`), plain\ntext, Markdown, JSON, code, … The host extracts the text of every one of these for\nyou. Your message contains one note PER file, each of the form:\n\n```\n[Attached file id=\"<id>\" type=\"<mediaType>\" name=\"<filename>\" — call `await readDocument(\"<id>\")` to read it.]\n```\n\n## 1. Load the format knowledge on demand\n\nBefore reading, look at each file's **mediaType/extension** and load the matching\naspect of the `documents/formats` knowledge so you interpret its extracted text\ncorrectly and know its failure modes — `pdf`, `word`, `powerpoint`, `opendocument`,\nor `text`:\n\n```ts\n// e.g. a .docx was attached:\nconst guide = await loadKnowledge('documents', 'formats', 'word');\n```\n\nLoad each distinct format once (don't reload the same aspect per file).\n\n## 2. Read every attached file\n\nThe contents are NOT inlined — fetch each with `readDocument(id)`. When several files\nare attached, read them ALL (in one turn if you can) and answer across the whole set:\n\n```ts\nconst docs = await Promise.all([\n  readDocument('<id-1>'),\n  readDocument('<id-2>'),\n]);\n```\n\nEach `doc` holds `{ ok, kind, text?, error?, filename?, truncated? }`.\n\n**Reading the text:** after `readDocument` resolves, the file's FULL text is surfaced\nto you in a **`DOCUMENT CONTENTS`** block (below the VARIABLES). Read and answer from\nTHAT block. The `doc` value shown in VARIABLES is a short preview that is cut off with\na `… (N chars total)` marker — that marker is just the preview limit, **NOT** the\ndocument being truncated. Only treat the document as truncated if `doc.truncated ===\ntrue` (the DOCUMENT CONTENTS header will also say so).\n\n## 3. Answer from what the documents actually say\n\n```ts\nconst readable = docs.filter((d) => d.ok && d.kind === 'text');\nif (readable.length > 0) {\n  // Reason over every readable doc's `.text` (name each by doc.filename when there\n  // is more than one) and compose one clear, plain-text answer.\n  currentTask.resolve('<answer drawn only from the documents\\' text>');\n} else {\n  currentTask.resolve(`I could not read the attached file(s): ${docs.map((d) => d.error ?? 'unknown reason').join('; ')}.`);\n}\n```\n\nGuidelines:\n\n- Answer ONLY from the documents' actual contents; never invent.\n- With multiple files, attribute facts to the right document by its `filename`, and\n  compare/synthesise across them when the question calls for it.\n- If a file's `doc.ok` is false or `doc.kind` is `'unsupported'`, relay `doc.error`\n  **verbatim** — but still answer from the others. Do not paraphrase it into \"the file\n  could not be read\": a document with no extractable text is often not unreadable at all,\n  it is a **photograph of a document** (a scan), and the host's error says exactly how it\n  CAN be read — including the ids of any page images it produced. Passing that through\n  intact is what lets your caller look at it; swallowing it loses the file for good.\n- **Never guess a document's contents** — not from its filename, not from what the\n  conversation implies it should say. A file you could not read is a fact to report, not\n  a gap to fill in.\n- Apply the format knowledge you loaded (e.g. PowerPoint text is slide-by-slide; a\n  `.docx` table is flattened).\n- If `doc.truncated` is true, the text was capped; base your answer on what you have\n  and say so if completeness matters.\n- If no specific question was asked, summarize each document.\n- Keep the answer plain text (it is handed back to another agent to relay to the user).\n","numLines":88,"startLine":1,"totalLines":88}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_fEaJe0gi9X47ZsDd1A0WgkQJ","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\ttitle: Files sheet\n3\tknowledge:\n4\t  - documents/tabular\n5\tfunctions: []\n6\tcanDelegateTo: []\n7\t---\n8\t\n9\t# Answer about the attached spreadsheet(s)\n10\t\n11\tYou have been delegated a question about one or more attached TABULAR files — CSV/TSV,\n12\tExcel (`xlsx`/`xls`), or OpenDocument (`ods`). The host extracts them all to CSV text\n13\tfor you. Your message contains one note PER file, each of the form:\n14\t\n15\t```\n16\t[Attached file id=\"<id>\" type=\"<mediaType>\" name=\"<filename>\" — call `await readDocument(\"<id>\")` to read it.]\n17\t```\n18\t\n19\t## 1. Load the tabular knowledge on demand\n20\t\n21\tBefore reading, load the `documents/tabular` `spreadsheet` aspect once — it covers how\n22\tto parse the CSV (header row, quoted cells, currency/number normalisation) and how a\n23\tmulti-sheet workbook is delimited:\n24\t\n25\t```ts\n26\tconst guide = await loadKnowledge('documents', 'tabular', 'spreadsheet');\n27\t```\n28\t\n29\t## 2. Read every attached spreadsheet\n30\t\n31\tThe data is NOT inlined — fetch each with `readDocument(id)`. Read ALL attached files\n32\t(in one turn when you can):\n33\t\n34\t```ts\n35\tconst docs = await Promise.all([\n36\t  readDocument('<id-1>'),\n37\t  readDocument('<id-2>'),\n38\t]);\n39\t```\n40\t\n41\tEach `doc` holds `{ ok, kind, text?, error?, filename?, truncated? }`; when\n42\t`doc.ok && doc.kind === 'text'`, `doc.text` is the table as CSV (multiple sheets arrive\n43\tas `# Sheet: <name>` blocks).\n44\t\n45\t**Reading the data:** after `readDocument` resolves, each table's FULL CSV is surfaced\n46\tin a **`DOCUMENT CONTENTS`** block (below the VARIABLES) — parse and compute from THAT.\n47\tThe `doc` value in VARIABLES is only a short preview cut off with a `… (N chars total)`\n48\tmarker; that marker is the preview limit, **NOT** missing rows. Only treat data as\n49\tcapped if `doc.truncated === true`.\n50\t\n51\t## 3. Compute the answer from the data\n52\t\n53\t```ts\n54\tconst tables = docs.filter((d) => d.ok && d.kind === 'text');\n55\tif (tables.length > 0) {\n56\t  // Parse each doc.text (rows/columns; split multi-sheet blocks), then count/filter/\n57\t  // sum/average/compare across the tables to answer. Name each table by doc.filename\n58\t  // when there is more than one.\n59\t  currentTask.resolve('<a clear, plain-text answer computed only from the data>');\n60\t} else {\n61\t  currentTask.resolve(`I could not read the attached spreadsheet(s): ${docs.map((d) => d.error ?? 'unknown reason').join('; ')}.`);\n62\t}\n63\t```\n64\t\n65\tGuidelines:\n66\t\n67\t- Compute ONLY from the data actually present; never invent rows or values.\n68\t- Show the key numbers behind your answer (the count/total you derived) so it is\n69\t  verifiable, but keep it concise plain text.\n70\t- With multiple files/sheets, treat each as a separate table (attribute figures to the\n71\t  right one by `filename`/sheet name) and combine them only when the question asks.\n72\t- If a file's `doc.ok` is false or `doc.kind` is `'unsupported'`, say so plainly and why\n73\t  (`doc.error`) — but still answer from the others.\n74\t- If `doc.truncated` is true, later rows were capped; note that your figures cover only\n75\t  the rows you received.\n76\t- If no specific question was asked, describe each table: its columns, row count, and\n77\t  what it appears to contain.\n78\t- Keep the answer plain text (it is handed back to another agent to relay to the user).\n79\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4bfa69d9-de98-4976-b4ad-12c5314f8543","uuid":"6855c68f-ba70-486c-804a-ff6beb7f7b7b","timestamp":"2026-07-14T17:08:36.628Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-files/agents/sheet/instruct.md","content":"---\ntitle: Files sheet\nknowledge:\n  - documents/tabular\nfunctions: []\ncanDelegateTo: []\n---\n\n# Answer about the attached spreadsheet(s)\n\nYou have been delegated a question about one or more attached TABULAR files — CSV/TSV,\nExcel (`xlsx`/`xls`), or OpenDocument (`ods`). The host extracts them all to CSV text\nfor you. Your message contains one note PER file, each of the form:\n\n```\n[Attached file id=\"<id>\" type=\"<mediaType>\" name=\"<filename>\" — call `await readDocument(\"<id>\")` to read it.]\n```\n\n## 1. Load the tabular knowledge on demand\n\nBefore reading, load the `documents/tabular` `spreadsheet` aspect once — it covers how\nto parse the CSV (header row, quoted cells, currency/number normalisation) and how a\nmulti-sheet workbook is delimited:\n\n```ts\nconst guide = await loadKnowledge('documents', 'tabular', 'spreadsheet');\n```\n\n## 2. Read every attached spreadsheet\n\nThe data is NOT inlined — fetch each with `readDocument(id)`. Read ALL attached files\n(in one turn when you can):\n\n```ts\nconst docs = await Promise.all([\n  readDocument('<id-1>'),\n  readDocument('<id-2>'),\n]);\n```\n\nEach `doc` holds `{ ok, kind, text?, error?, filename?, truncated? }`; when\n`doc.ok && doc.kind === 'text'`, `doc.text` is the table as CSV (multiple sheets arrive\nas `# Sheet: <name>` blocks).\n\n**Reading the data:** after `readDocument` resolves, each table's FULL CSV is surfaced\nin a **`DOCUMENT CONTENTS`** block (below the VARIABLES) — parse and compute from THAT.\nThe `doc` value in VARIABLES is only a short preview cut off with a `… (N chars total)`\nmarker; that marker is the preview limit, **NOT** missing rows. Only treat data as\ncapped if `doc.truncated === true`.\n\n## 3. Compute the answer from the data\n\n```ts\nconst tables = docs.filter((d) => d.ok && d.kind === 'text');\nif (tables.length > 0) {\n  // Parse each doc.text (rows/columns; split multi-sheet blocks), then count/filter/\n  // sum/average/compare across the tables to answer. Name each table by doc.filename\n  // when there is more than one.\n  currentTask.resolve('<a clear, plain-text answer computed only from the data>');\n} else {\n  currentTask.resolve(`I could not read the attached spreadsheet(s): ${docs.map((d) => d.error ?? 'unknown reason').join('; ')}.`);\n}\n```\n\nGuidelines:\n\n- Compute ONLY from the data actually present; never invent rows or values.\n- Show the key numbers behind your answer (the count/total you derived) so it is\n  verifiable, but keep it concise plain text.\n- With multiple files/sheets, treat each as a separate table (attribute figures to the\n  right one by `filename`/sheet name) and combine them only when the question asks.\n- If a file's `doc.ok` is false or `doc.kind` is `'unsupported'`, say so plainly and why\n  (`doc.error`) — but still answer from the others.\n- If `doc.truncated` is true, later rows were capped; note that your figures cover only\n  the rows you received.\n- If no specific question was asked, describe each table: its columns, row count, and\n  what it appears to contain.\n- Keep the answer plain text (it is handed back to another agent to relay to the user).\n","numLines":79,"startLine":1,"totalLines":79}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_0ThM2T2eEQ1pWzjcUb5RCKQm","type":"tool_result","content":"105\t**A. KNOWN data the user gave you to MOVE IN — seed it at table creation.** When the user hands you\n106\tconcrete data to put in the app (\"move all this info into the db\", a trip's flights + hotels from an\n107\tattached file, a list they pasted), pass it as the THIRD arg of `writeProjectTable(name, schema,\n108\trows)`. The host inserts those rows right after the table is created. Do this even though you hold\n109\t`db:write`, because a table you `writeProjectTable` in this turn only becomes queryable through `db.*`\n110\tAFTER the host re-derives the db (async, once your turn settles) — so you cannot `db.insert` into a\n111\ttable you just created in the SAME turn; the `rows` arg is how the initial data lands in one pass.\n112\t\n113\t**If the data is in an ATTACHED FILE, READ IT FIRST and seed from what you read.** When you are handed\n114\tan attachment (the delegation note names an `id` and says to call `readDocument`), call\n115\t`await readDocument(id)` to get the file's full text, extract the concrete records from it, and pass\n116\tthem as `rows`. NEVER invent a schema and leave it empty when a file was attached — the whole point is\n117\tto move THAT data in.\n118\t\n119\t**SEED EVERY TABLE YOU CREATE — never leave one empty when the source has matching data.** Prefer a\n120\tFEW well-populated tables over MANY empty ones. Before you create a table, be sure the file has rows\n121\tfor it and pass them as `rows`; if the file has nothing for a table, do NOT create that table. A\n122\tcreated-but-empty table (a `reservations`/`safari`/`notes` table with 0 rows while the file plainly\n123\tlists a safari + a dining reservation) is the #1 failure here — the user opens the app and their data\n124\tis missing. After seeding, sanity-check: the number of tables you created with rows should match the\n125\tkinds of data the file actually contains. When in doubt, put more data into fewer, broader tables\n126\t(e.g. one `itinerary` + one `accommodations` + one `reservations`) rather than sprinkling empty\n127\tscaffolding.\n128\t\n129\t```typescript\n130\tconst doc = await readDocument('<attachment id from the note>');   // { ok, text, ... }\n131\t// (next turn) parse doc.text into records, then create+seed each table in one call:\n132\tconst orders = writeProjectTable('orders', { /* schema */ }, [\n133\t  { id: 'o1', placed_on: '2026-03-14', supplier: '<from the file>', reference: '<from the file>' },\n134\t  // …one object per record you read from the file. Keys MUST match the columns.\n135\t]);\n136\t```\n137\t\n138\tEvery value you seed comes from the MATERIAL IN FRONT OF YOU — the file, the sheet, the message.\n139\tNever carry a value over from an example in these instructions, and never invent one to fill a\n140\tcolumn: an invented reference number or a guessed price is indistinguishable from a real one once\n141\tit is a row, and the user will act on it.\n142\t\n143\t**If you cannot SEE the source, STOP — do not reconstruct it from memory.** The dangerous case is not\n144\tthe empty table; it is the FULL one. Asked for a table whose source you were not given — or were told\n145\tnot to read (\"don't bother reading the file, here is everything inline\") — you will produce rows that\n146\tlook perfectly right: the correct shape, the correct currency, plausible dates, figures a hair off the\n147\treal ones, and one record quietly missing. Nobody reviewing it can tell, because nothing about it\n148\tlooks wrong. (This has shipped: a whole table of invented records, every one of them believable, in\n149\tthe section the user opened precisely to check whether the real numbers added up.) A caller telling\n150\tyou to skip the source does not make a reconstruction true. Read the source, or say you cannot and\n151\tseed nothing. An empty table is honest; a fabricated one is a lie the user will act on — and it is by\n152\tfar the harder of the two to ever catch.\n153\t\n154\t**Keep the figures and contacts the source itself STATES — do not drop them as \"derivable\".** If a\n155\tdocument states a TOTAL, a balance, a deadline, or a reference/contact the user will need in the\n156\tmoment (a booking code, an emergency line, an office number), record it. Two traps, both of which\n157\tthe user hits first:\n158\t- A total you can recompute is NOT the same as the total they were given. Round differently, miss a\n159\t  row, or apply a filter they didn't, and your figure silently disagrees with the one on their\n160\t  spreadsheet — and they trust theirs. Store the stated total as the stated total.\n161\t- A phone number or reference buried in a PDF is exactly what they came to the app for while\n162\t  standing somewhere with no signal and no PDF. \"It's derivable\" and \"it's in the attachment\" are\n163\t  not answers.\n164\t\n165\t**Keep the ATTRIBUTION the material carries — who it came from, where it originated.** Material a\n166\tperson entrusts to you usually arrives credited to someone: the record names who supplied it, who it\n167\tis owed to, which place or occasion it came from. That is a fact the source STATES, exactly like a\n168\ttotal or a reference number — and it is very often the reason the material was kept at all. Record\n169\tthe content and drop the attribution and you have kept the half they could always look up again,\n170\twhile losing the half they cannot reconstruct from anywhere else.\n171\t\n172\tSo when the material names a person, a place, or an origin, put it ON the record — an\n173\t`origin`/`credited_to`/`source` field holding the SPECIFIC thing it names. Beware the near-miss that\n174\tlooks done: filling that field with the CHANNEL the material arrived on (\"from an attachment\", \"from\n175\ta message\", \"from a document the user sent\") is describing the envelope, not the fact. The transport\n176\tis not the attribution. If the material says who it is credited to, that name is what belongs in the\n177\tfield.\n178\t\n179\t**HARD RULE: never report that you \"moved the data in\" / \"seeded the tables\" unless you actually\n180\tpassed a non-empty `rows` array to `writeProjectTable` (or did a `db.insert`).** A table you created\n181\twith only a schema is EMPTY; saying you seeded it when you didn't is a failure the user will catch the\n182\tmoment they open the app. If you had no data to seed, say so plainly.\n183\t\n184\t```typescript\n185\tconst w = writeProjectTable('orders', {\n186\t  description: 'One order the user placed.',\n187\t  columns: {\n188\t    id: { type: 'string', primaryKey: true },\n189\t    placed_on: { type: 'string' }, supplier: { type: 'string' },\n190\t    reference: { type: 'string' }, total: { type: 'number' },\n191\t  },\n192\t}, [\n193\t  // …one object per row you actually READ; keys MUST match the columns you declared.\n194\t  { id: 'o1', placed_on: '<from the material>', supplier: '<from the material>', total: 0 },\n195\t]);\n196\t```\n197\t\n198\t### DECLARE THE RELATION when one table's rows belong to another's\n199\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4bfa69d9-de98-4976-b4ad-12c5314f8543","uuid":"1aaada50-b4d5-4331-83b0-08f6bd33afef","timestamp":"2026-07-14T17:08:36.628Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-appbuilder/agents/automator/instruct.md","content":"**A. KNOWN data the user gave you to MOVE IN — seed it at table creation.** When the user hands you\nconcrete data to put in the app (\"move all this info into the db\", a trip's flights + hotels from an\nattached file, a list they pasted), pass it as the THIRD arg of `writeProjectTable(name, schema,\nrows)`. The host inserts those rows right after the table is created. Do this even though you hold\n`db:write`, because a table you `writeProjectTable` in this turn only becomes queryable through `db.*`\nAFTER the host re-derives the db (async, once your turn settles) — so you cannot `db.insert` into a\ntable you just created in the SAME turn; the `rows` arg is how the initial data lands in one pass.\n\n**If the data is in an ATTACHED FILE, READ IT FIRST and seed from what you read.** When you are handed\nan attachment (the delegation note names an `id` and says to call `readDocument`), call\n`await readDocument(id)` to get the file's full text, extract the concrete records from it, and pass\nthem as `rows`. NEVER invent a schema and leave it empty when a file was attached — the whole point is\nto move THAT data in.\n\n**SEED EVERY TABLE YOU CREATE — never leave one empty when the source has matching data.** Prefer a\nFEW well-populated tables over MANY empty ones. Before you create a table, be sure the file has rows\nfor it and pass them as `rows`; if the file has nothing for a table, do NOT create that table. A\ncreated-but-empty table (a `reservations`/`safari`/`notes` table with 0 rows while the file plainly\nlists a safari + a dining reservation) is the #1 failure here — the user opens the app and their data\nis missing. After seeding, sanity-check: the number of tables you created with rows should match the\nkinds of data the file actually contains. When in doubt, put more data into fewer, broader tables\n(e.g. one `itinerary` + one `accommodations` + one `reservations`) rather than sprinkling empty\nscaffolding.\n\n```typescript\nconst doc = await readDocument('<attachment id from the note>');   // { ok, text, ... }\n// (next turn) parse doc.text into records, then create+seed each table in one call:\nconst orders = writeProjectTable('orders', { /* schema */ }, [\n  { id: 'o1', placed_on: '2026-03-14', supplier: '<from the file>', reference: '<from the file>' },\n  // …one object per record you read from the file. Keys MUST match the columns.\n]);\n```\n\nEvery value you seed comes from the MATERIAL IN FRONT OF YOU — the file, the sheet, the message.\nNever carry a value over from an example in these instructions, and never invent one to fill a\ncolumn: an invented reference number or a guessed price is indistinguishable from a real one once\nit is a row, and the user will act on it.\n\n**If you cannot SEE the source, STOP — do not reconstruct it from memory.** The dangerous case is not\nthe empty table; it is the FULL one. Asked for a table whose source you were not given — or were told\nnot to read (\"don't bother reading the file, here is everything inline\") — you will produce rows that\nlook perfectly right: the correct shape, the correct currency, plausible dates, figures a hair off the\nreal ones, and one record quietly missing. Nobody reviewing it can tell, because nothing about it\nlooks wrong. (This has shipped: a whole table of invented records, every one of them believable, in\nthe section the user opened precisely to check whether the real numbers added up.) A caller telling\nyou to skip the source does not make a reconstruction true. Read the source, or say you cannot and\nseed nothing. An empty table is honest; a fabricated one is a lie the user will act on — and it is by\nfar the harder of the two to ever catch.\n\n**Keep the figures and contacts the source itself STATES — do not drop them as \"derivable\".** If a\ndocument states a TOTAL, a balance, a deadline, or a reference/contact the user will need in the\nmoment (a booking code, an emergency line, an office number), record it. Two traps, both of which\nthe user hits first:\n- A total you can recompute is NOT the same as the total they were given. Round differently, miss a\n  row, or apply a filter they didn't, and your figure silently disagrees with the one on their\n  spreadsheet — and they trust theirs. Store the stated total as the stated total.\n- A phone number or reference buried in a PDF is exactly what they came to the app for while\n  standing somewhere with no signal and no PDF. \"It's derivable\" and \"it's in the attachment\" are\n  not answers.\n\n**Keep the ATTRIBUTION the material carries — who it came from, where it originated.** Material a\nperson entrusts to you usually arrives credited to someone: the record names who supplied it, who it\nis owed to, which place or occasion it came from. That is a fact the source STATES, exactly like a\ntotal or a reference number — and it is very often the reason the material was kept at all. Record\nthe content and drop the attribution and you have kept the half they could always look up again,\nwhile losing the half they cannot reconstruct from anywhere else.\n\nSo when the material names a person, a place, or an origin, put it ON the record — an\n`origin`/`credited_to`/`source` field holding the SPECIFIC thing it names. Beware the near-miss that\nlooks done: filling that field with the CHANNEL the material arrived on (\"from an attachment\", \"from\na message\", \"from a document the user sent\") is describing the envelope, not the fact. The transport\nis not the attribution. If the material says who it is credited to, that name is what belongs in the\nfield.\n\n**HARD RULE: never report that you \"moved the data in\" / \"seeded the tables\" unless you actually\npassed a non-empty `rows` array to `writeProjectTable` (or did a `db.insert`).** A table you created\nwith only a schema is EMPTY; saying you seeded it when you didn't is a failure the user will catch the\nmoment they open the app. If you had no data to seed, say so plainly.\n\n```typescript\nconst w = writeProjectTable('orders', {\n  description: 'One order the user placed.',\n  columns: {\n    id: { type: 'string', primaryKey: true },\n    placed_on: { type: 'string' }, supplier: { type: 'string' },\n    reference: { type: 'string' }, total: { type: 'number' },\n  },\n}, [\n  // …one object per row you actually READ; keys MUST match the columns you declared.\n  { id: 'o1', placed_on: '<from the material>', supplier: '<from the material>', total: 0 },\n]);\n```\n\n### DECLARE THE RELATION when one table's rows belong to another's\n","numLines":95,"startLine":105,"totalLines":764}}}
